Since we know that $f(91)=1$ and that the odd powers of a number are symmetric about zero, we have \begin{align*}
    f(x)&amp;=ax^6+bx^4-cx^2+3\\
    f(-x)&amp;=a(-x)^6+b(-x)^4-c(-x)^2+3\\
    &amp;=ax^6-bx^4+cx^2+3.
\end{align*}We want to know $f(91)+f(-91)$. Substituting in our expressions for f(x) and f(-x), we get $$f(91)+f(-91)=(a\cdot 91^6+b\cdot 91^4-c\cdot 91^2+3)+(a\cdot (-91)^6+b\cdot (-91)^4-c\cdot (-91)^2+3).$$ Because the odd powers of a number are symmetric about zero, we know that $$a(-x)^6=a(x)^6,$$ and $$(a(-x)^6+a(x)^6)=2a(x)^6.$$ In addition to this, $$(b(-x)^4-b(x)^4) = 0,$$ because the even powers of a number are symmetric about zero. And for the term $-cx^2$, we have $$c(-x)^2=c(x)^2,$$ so \begin{align*}
    f(91)+f(-91)&amp;=(a\cdot 91^6+b\cdot 91^4-c\cdot 91^2+3)+(a\cdot (-91)^6+b\cdot (-91)^4-c\cdot (-91)^2+3)\\
    &amp;=2a(91)^6+(b\cdot (-91)^4-c(-91)^2+3)+2a(-91)^6.
\end{align*}The $2a(91)^6$ and $2a(-91)^6$ terms add up to zero, because these two expressions are symmetric about zero. Therefore we only have \begin{align*}
    f(91)+f(-91)&amp;=b\cdot (-91)^4-c(-91)^2+3\\
    &amp;=b(-91^4)-c(-91^2)+3\\
    &amp;=-b(91^4)+c(91^2)+3.
\end{align*} Since we are given that $f(91) = 1$, we can find the value of f(-91). To do this, let us first note that \begin{align*}
    a(91)^6+b(91)^4-c(91^2)+3&amp;=1\\
    \Rightarrow\qquad a(91)^6&=1-b(91)^4+c(91^2)-3\\
    &amp;=-b(91^4)+c(91^2)-2.
\end{align*}Then we have that $f(-91)=a(91^6)+b(91^4) - c(91^2)+3=-[1-b(91)^4+c(91^2)-2]+3$. Substituting in this expression for f(-91), we get \begin{align*}
    f(91)+f(-91)&amp;=a(91)^6+b(91)^4-c(91^2)+3+[-1-b(91)^4+c(91^2)-2]+3\\
    &amp;=-b(91^4)+c(91^2)-2+[-1-b(91^4)+c(91^2)-2]+3\\
    &amp;=2(-b(91^4)+c(91^2))-5.
\end{align*}Since we are given that $f(91)=1$, it follows that \begin{align*}
    f(91)+f(-91)&amp;=2(-b(91^4)+c(91^2))-5\\
    &amp;=\boxed{-6}.
\end{align*}
